-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Air Mauritius, National Bank of Kenya
-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 2012-01-20T16:51:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-20/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-air-mauritius-national-bank-of-kenya.html
 The  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  rose
for the seventh day, adding 0.5 percent to 903.45 in Windhoek,
the highest level since Feb. 21.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  fell for a fourth day, declining
0.3 percent to 54.66 in Nairobi, the lowest since Jan. 4. The
 Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  lost 0.4 percent to
20,820.32 at the close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed
statement from the bourse. Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  declined for
a third day, losing 0.6 percent to 1,852.89 by the end of
trading.  The following shares were active in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Air Mauritius Ltd. (AML)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s fourth-
biggest airline, declined for a seventh day, falling 2.2 percent
to 13.5 rupees, its longest losing streak in more than eight
years.  “The decline is on concerns arising from the reduction in
arrivals noted in December, the best month of the year for the
 tourism industry ,” Kishen Nadassen, a senior research analyst
at CIM Stockbrokers Ltd., said in a phone interview from the
capital Port Louis. “Should the situation persist in January,
we could expect the airline’s performance to be much affected.”  National Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (NBKL KN), a state-owned
lender, plunged 5.7 percent to 20.75 shillings, the biggest
decline since Nov. 30. The Nairobi-based bank said Managing
Director Reuben Marambii, who was appointed in 1999, will retire
at the end of this year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
